{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503803","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503803"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:07:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:07:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2083"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2083","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2083"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.36,0.36,0.19,0.01,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2083"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43140"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2083","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2083"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2083"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28139"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1979"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"6610"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"198"},{"type":"contributions","id":"221"},{"type":"contributions","id":"730"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11013"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11080"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44271"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43140","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43140"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old woman is recovering in hospital after treatment of left lower limb cellulitis. She has a medical history of atrial fibrillation, type 2 diabetes mellitus, and vitamin B12 deficiency. Her current medications include three days of oral flucloxacillin and regular paracetamol, apixaban, metformin, and vitamin B12 supplements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination she appears well. The pulse rate is 60/min, blood pressure 135/75mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. The erythema and pain in her left leg has resolved and physical examination is otherwise unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe white cell count and C-reactive protein have normalised. The complete blood examination (CBE) today reveals normal haemoglobin and a platelet count of 50 x 10^9/L (150-400). Peripheral blood smear shows platelet clumping.Previous CBEs have shown a normal platelet count.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause for this patient\u0027s low platelet count?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Drug induced thrombocytopaenia","Pseudothrombocytopaenia","Immune-mediated thrombocytopenic purpura (ITP)","Vitamin B12 deficiency","DIC (disseminated intravascular coagulation)"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s platelet count is likely artificially low (\u003Cstrong\u003Epseudothrombocytopaenia\u003C/strong\u003E). Pseudothrombocytopenia should always be considered in a patient with a sudden drop in platelet count, with previously normal platelet counts, without an obvious cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of fibrin strands, platelet aggregates and platelet satellites in a blood sample may cause a falsely low platelet count. The presence of large clots in a blood sample would invalidate all results associated with that sample. A blood film should be examined to confirm or rule out these factors as a cause of a low platelet count.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrug\u2010induced thrombocytopaenia (DITP\u003C/strong\u003E) is an important consideration. Development of DITP is associated with a range of medications, most frequently quinine drugs and sulfonamides. Thrombocytopaenia typically develops 1\u20132\u00a0weeks after exposure, thus a thorough drug history is critical.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBone marrow failure\u003C/strong\u003E can cause low platelets, but would usually present with other abnormalities on the CBE such as anaemia or leukopenia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMost cases of \u003Cstrong\u003Eimmune thrombocytopenic purpura (ITP) \u003C/strong\u003Eare acute, often occurring within a few weeks of recovering from a viral illness. Pseudothrombocytopenia can occur due to platelet clumping during blood sampling, leading to falsely low platelet counts. This can be confirmed by repeating the platelet count with a different anticoagulant, such as EDTA. In ITP, repeated platelet counts consistently show low levels due to ongoing immune-mediated destruction. ITP is an autoimmune disorder characterized by immune-mediated destruction of platelets, typically presenting with mucocutaneous bleeding like petechiae and purpura. However, in this case, the patient\u0027s clinical presentation, including the resolution of cellulitis and absence of bleeding symptoms, makes ITP less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVitamin B12 deficiency:\u003C/strong\u003E Vitamin B12 deficiency can lead to various hematological abnormalities, including macrocytic anemia and thrombocytopenia. However, it typically presents with neurological symptoms (such as peripheral neuropathy or cognitive impairment) and macrocytic anemia. In this case, the absence of neurological symptoms and normal hemoglobin levels make vitamin B12 deficiency less likely as the primary cause of thrombocytopenia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisseminated intravascular coagulation \u003C/strong\u003E(DIC)\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eis a systemic process characterised by widespread activation of coagulation, leading to consumption of platelets and clotting factors, resulting in thrombocytopenia and abnormal coagulation parameters. While these conditions can cause thrombocytopenia, they are typically associated with other clinical features such as bleeding, organ dysfunction, or abnormal coagulation parameters. In this case, the absence of these additional findings makes DIC less likely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Pseudothrombocytopenia should always be considered in a patient with a sudden drop in platelet count, with previously normal platelet counts, without an obvious cause."],"references":["Sharma S, Rose H. Incidentally detected thrombocytopaenia in adults. Aust J Gen Pract. 2014;43:700-4. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2014/october/incidentally-detected-thrombocytopaenia-in-adults","Smock K, Perkins S. Thrombocytopenia: an update. Int J Lab Hemat. 2014;36(3):269-278. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24750673/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28139"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2083"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28139","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/28139"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-03-03T02:51:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-03-03T02:51:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2083"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43140"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,